Chemical Structure Infrared spectroscopy is well established for studies of protein structure. The advantage is that vibrational signatures can be correlated to the secondary structures in protein molecules [34]. However, surprisingly few reports on application of infrared spectroscopic ellipsometry (IRSE) for studies of protein layers are found in the literature in spite of that IRSE has the advantage to provide a quantification of the amount of protein on a surface, i.e. to determine the layer thickness in addition to the IR spectral features. The limited use of IRSE may be due to that the instrumentation is rather expensive and slow. With a pyroelectric DTGS detector, a typical measurement on a protein monolayer may take 12 h or more but using other types of detectors can shorten the measurement time. A rather large sample area of several mm\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
